Hesiod does not actually mention the virtue of the first men, but it stands out by con· trast with the corruption of their successors. On the other hand, in Jewish prophecy righteousness is the most prominent note of the final reign of blessedness. Virgil’s meaning here is much the same as in Georg. i. 500, where he prays that the young Augustus may be permitted “everso suc· currere saeclo . . . ubi fas versum atque nefas, tot bella per orbem, tam multae scelerum facies.'’
